   {:e #blake3 "6bcf9feba4971e5b395f8c4f2d42d6725b05fe91af573b20f207ebc365a31fda" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "The Convergence Thesis — braid learns what coherence means; THE CONVERGENCE THESIS: Braid should converge on the optimal coherence model for any domain through closed-loop empirical learning. The initial policy is a Bayesian prior. Every observation is evidence. The calibration loop computes the posterior. The gradient selects the experiment. This resolves ALL review problems simultaneously: F(S) accuracy, task overload, footer noise, performance, witness gaps. OBSERVER-4 (calibration) should be P0, not P1 — it is the reason the policy manifest exists. Without calibration, the manifest is a static guess. With calibration, it is a learning system. The system does not just maintain coherence. It learns what coherence means.; Session entity: :recon/trace-1b380c59c6440b56; FOUNDATIONAL QUESTION: Is the DDIS epistemological model optimal for AI-powered software development? Is the epistemic bootstrap complete? How would we know? The spec and substrate have evolved significantly (braid is now an epistemology runtime, not just a spec tool) but the DDIS methodology (INV/ADR/NEG, bilateral loop, 7-component F(S)) has remained relatively static since inception. Is there a divergence between what we now understand and what the methodology encodes?; TASK TREE REVISION: OBSERVER-4 (calibration loop) promoted from P1 to P0 and moved into Proposal 1 critical path. It comes after POLICY-4 (views) and before POLICY-REGRESSION (tests). The calibration loop IS the policy manifests reason for existence. Without it, the manifest is a static configuration. With it, the manifest is a learning system that converges on the optimal coherence model empirically.; Session entity: :task/t-5be02014; Session entity: :recon/trace-cea753f63b1f6dd2; ANSWER TO OPTIMALITY QUESTION: DDIS does not need to be optimal. It needs to be good enough to start the convergence loop. The substrate makes the policys optimality MEASURABLE via calibration error (predicted vs actual F(S) delta). A decreasing calibration error means the policy is converging toward optimality. DDIS is a good initial policy because INV/ADR/NEG capture the three primary knowledge types and the bilateral loop catches the primary failure mode. But the FINAL policy is whatever OBSERVER-4 converges to after enough real use. The bootstrap matters not because it must be perfect, but because it determines where exploration begins.; Session entity: :task/t-ff07bb5a; SYNTHESIS: The DDIS optimality question resolves through the policy manifest. The four-gap analysis (goals, constraints, observations, patterns) suggests DDIS should expand from 4 to 8 element types. But with the policy manifest, this expansion is just a manifest change: add goal, constraint, observation, and pattern as claim types in ddis.edn with appropriate boundary definitions. No kernel change needed. The optimality of the DDIS policy becomes an empirical question answered by the calibration loop (OBSERVER-4), not a design question answered by reasoning. The key insight: the substrate makes all policy questions empirical, which means the bootstrap only needs to be good enough, not perfect.; Session entity: :task/t-38c1e936" :op :assert}
